// 49-fn-handle-rooting — m53: free-fn implicit-locus
// handle-rooting.
//
// m49 shipped the *arena* half of spec/memory.md "Free `fn`
// functions": every non-main free fn opens a per-call subregion
// of the caller's arena, body allocations route through it, and
// heap-typed returns deep-copy back into the caller's arena
// before the subregion is destroyed. m53 ships the *lifecycle*
// half: per spec, "the function returns when: (a) body's last
// statement completes, AND (b) all children of the implicit
// locus have dissolved." Pre-m53 the typed-return path silently
// popped the deferred-dissolves frame opened at fn entry without
// flushing it, leaking long-lived loci bound in the fn body.
//
// Concretely: any locus with `bus subscribe` or `bus publish` is
// long-lived — its dissolve gets deferred to the enclosing
// frame's exit. m53 closes the gap by hoisting
// `flush_dissolve_frame` from the body-fall-through arm into
// `emit_fn_exit_epilogue`, so every free-fn exit (open-end,
// `return;`, `return v;`) flushes uniformly. The flush drains
// the bus queue first (so any cells the body's loci published
// during their birth() get dispatched while subscribers are
// still alive), then dissolves the bound handles in reverse
// order.
//
// This example exercises both the bus-traffic path and the
// dissolution-order path:
//
//   make_pair(n) -> Int binds two long-lived loci:
//     - Watcher subscribes to "evt" — its on_evt fires when a
//       message arrives.
//     - Pulse publishes "evt" in birth() — that publish enqueues
//       a cell for Watcher.
//   Then make_pair returns n + 1 (typed return, exercises the
//   m53 fix specifically).
//
// Pre-m53 sequence: Pulse births → publishes "evt" → cell sits
// in queue. make_pair returns 7. Watcher + Pulse stay registered
// in the bus router (never deregistered because never dissolved).
// At main exit, the queue drain fires Watcher.on_evt → prints
// "watcher got". But Watcher and Pulse arenas leak.
//
// Post-m53: Pulse births → publishes → cell enqueued. make_pair
// hits return → flush at fn.exit drains queue (fires Watcher's
// on_evt while still alive) → dissolves Pulse → dissolves
// Watcher. By the time make_pair returns, all in-fn-bound loci
// are gone. The remainder of main runs, prints the return value,
// exits cleanly with no leaked handles.
//
// Output is identical between backends because the interpreter
// uses Rust ownership (Rc<RefCell>) — its lifetime model already
// satisfies the spec without an explicit handle-rooting pass.

type Msg {
    v: Int;
}

locus Watcher {
    bus {
        subscribe "evt" as on_evt of type Msg;
    }
    fn on_evt(m: Msg) {
        println("watcher got: ", m.v);
    }
}

locus Pulse {
    bus {
        publish "evt" of type Msg;
    }
    birth() {
        "evt" <- Msg { v: 42 };
    }
}

fn make_pair(n: Int) -> Int {
    let _w = Watcher { };
    let _p = Pulse { };
    return n + 1;
}

fn main() {
    let r: Int = make_pair(6);
    println("r = ", r);
}
